<BR>   I was fooling around with chaining pets last night, thinking that I ought to at least add it to the bag of tricks.  I happened to be in Lavastorm, so I tried the firescale croc (an even con, level 30).  Sent in the first pet fully equipped and buffed, and then followed up with others, naked but for fire shields.  My technique is undoubtedly a bit sloppy; I probably could have gotten in a few more ticks of med and a few more hits out of each pet.  I finished the battle with half a bubble of mana, going through four or five pets in the process.<P>   "Nifty", I thought, "I can still solo evens, even if it does cost a backpack full of malachite."<P>   Later on, though, I was in Guk, taking a look at the ancient crocodile.  (Hey, if I can kill level 30 crocs, might as well be one with something I can use.)  Some of those saltwater crocs also conned even.  I took one of those fairly handily by just nuking and healing, with about two bubbles of mana left and a pretty abused, but still living, pet.  (Probably a relatively good one.  He was hitting for 20, so I booted him and called up another, which proceeded to only hit for 19... crocs are too tough to see the 28s, I guess.)<P>   So, I'm still puzzled.  Perhaps the saltwaters are just easier targets than the firescale.  Certainly, /con isn't the whole story on how tough things fight.  Or perhaps my chaining technique is so bad as to conceal the effectiveness of the tactic.  Is pet chaining really especially powerful, or is it just another neat tactic we can use to keep things interesting?<P>   Thoughts?<BR>
